579-kmalloc()) for the allocation, but rejects flags used to specify a memory\nDocumentation/core-api/pin_user_pages.rst-211-\nDocumentation/core-api/pin_user_pages.rst-212-        static inline bool folio_maybe_dma_pinned(struct folio *folio)\nDocumentation/core-api/pin_user_pages.rst-213-\nDocumentation/core-api/pin_user_pages.rst-214-...is a prerequisite to solving the long-running gup+DMA problem.\nDocumentation/core-api/pin_user_pages.rst-215-\nDocumentation/core-api/pin_user_pages.rst-216-Another way of thinking about FOLL_GET, FOLL_PIN, and FOLL_LONGTERM\nDocumentation/core-api/pin_user_pages.rst-217-===================================================================\nDocumentation/core-api/pin_user_pages.rst-218-\nDocumentation/core-api/pin_user_pages.rst-219-Another way of thinking about these flags is as a progression of restrictions:\nDocumentation/core-api/pin_user_pages.rst-220-FOLL_GET is for struct page manipulation, without affecting the data that the\nDocumentation/core-api/pin_user_pages.rst:221:struct page refers to. FOLL_PIN is a *replacement* for FOLL_GET, and is for\nDocumentation/core-api/pin_user_pages.rst-222-short term pins on pages whose data *will* get accessed. As such, FOLL_PIN is\nDocumentation/core-api/pin_user_pages.rst-223-a \"more severe\" form of pinning. And finally, FOLL_LONGTERM is an even more\nDocumentation/core-api/pin_user_pages.rst-224-restrictive case that has FOLL_PIN as a prerequisite: this is for pages that\nDocumentation/core-api/pin_user_pages.rst-225-will be pinned longterm, and whose data will be accessed.\nDocumentation/core-api/pin_user_pages.rst-226-\nDocumentation/core-api/pin_user_pages.rst-227-Unit testing\nDocumentation/core-api/pin_user_pages.rst-228-============\nDocumentation/core-api/pin_user_pages.rst-229-This file::\nDocumentation/core-api/pin_user_pages.rst-230-\nDocumentation/core-api/pin_user_pages.rst-231- tools/testing/selftests/mm/gup_test.c\nDocumentation/mm/hmm.rst-116-specific commands in it to perform the update (unmap, cache invalidations, and\nDocumentation/mm/hmm.rst-117-flush, ...). This cannot be done through common code for all devices. Hence\nDocumentation/mm/hmm.rst-118-why HMM provides helpers to factor out everything that can be while leaving the\nDocumentation/mm/hmm.rst-119-hardware specific details to the device driver.\nDocumentation/mm/hmm.rst-120-\nDocumentation/mm/hmm.rst-121-The second mechanism HMM provides is a new kind of ZONE_DEVICE memory that\nDocumentation/mm/hmm.rst-122-allows allocating a struct page for each page of device memory. Those pages\nDocumentation/mm/hmm.rst-123-are special because the CPU cannot map them. However, they allow migrating\nDocumentation/mm/hmm.rst-124-main memory to device memory using existing migration mechanisms and everything\nDocumentation/mm/hmm.rst-125-looks like a page that is swapped out to disk from the CPU point of view. Using a\nDocumentation/mm/hmm.rst:126:struct page gives the easiest and cleanest integration with existing mm\nDocumentation/mm/hmm.rst-127-mechanisms. Here again, HMM only provides helpers, first to hotplug new ZONE_DEVICE\nDocumentation/mm/hmm.rst-128-memory for the device memory and second to perform migration. Policy decisions\nDocumentation/mm/hmm.rst-129-of what and when to migrate is left to the device driver.\nDocumentation/mm/hmm.rst-130-\nDocumentation/mm/hmm.rst-131-Note that any CPU access to a device page triggers a page fault and a migration\nDocumentation/mm/hmm.rst-132-back to main memory. For example, when a page backing a given CPU address A is\nDocumentation/mm/hmm.rst-133-migrated from a main memory page to a device page, then any CPU access to\nDocumentation/mm/hmm.rst-134-address A triggers a page fault and initiates a migration back to main memory.\nDocumentation/mm/hmm.rst-135-\nDocumentation/mm/hmm.rst-136-With these two features, HMM not only allows a device to mirror process address\nDocumentation/mm/memory-model.rst-11-for the CPU. Then there could be several contiguous ranges at\nDocumentation/mm/memory-model.rst-12-completely distinct addresses. And, don't forget about NUMA, where\nDocumentation/mm/memory-model.rst-13-different memory banks are attached to different CPUs.\nDocumentation/mm/memory-model.rst-14-\nDocumentation/mm/memory-model.rst-15-Linux abstracts this diversity using one of the two memory models:\nDocumentation/mm/memory-model.rst-16-FLATMEM and SPARSEMEM. Each architecture defines what\nDocumentation/mm/memory-model.rst-17-memory models it supports, what the default memory model is and\nDocumentation/mm/memory-model.rst-18-whether it is possible to manually override that default.\nDocumentation/mm/memory-model.rst-19-\nDocumentation/mm/memory-model.rst-20-All the memory models track the status of physical page frames using\nDocumentation/mm/memory-model.rst:21:struct page arranged in one or more arrays.\nDocumentation/mm/memory-model.rst-22-\nDocumentation/mm/memory-model.rst-23-Regardless of the selected memory model, there exists one-to-one\nDocumentation/mm/memory-model.rst-24-mapping between the physical page frame number (PFN) and the\nDocumentation/mm/memory-model.rst-25-corresponding `struct page`.\nDocumentation/mm/memory-model.rst-26-\nDocumentation/mm/memory-model.rst-27-Each memory model defines :c:func:`pfn_to_page` and :c:func:`page_to_pfn`\nDocumentation/mm/memory-model.rst-28-helpers that allow the conversion from PFN to `struct page` and vice\nDocumentation/mm/memory-model.rst-29-versa.\nDocumentation/mm/memory-model.rst-30-\nDocumentation/mm/memory-model.rst-31-FLATMEM\ndrivers/char/agp/generic.c-1207-\ndrivers/char/agp/generic.c-1208-#ifdef CONFIG_X86\ndrivers/char/agp/generic.c-1209-\tset_pages_array_uc(mem->pages, num_pages);\ndrivers/char/agp/generic.c-1210-#endif\ndrivers/char/agp/generic.c-1211-\tret = 0;\ndrivers/char/agp/generic.c-1212-out:\ndrivers/char/agp/generic.c-1213-\treturn ret;\ndrivers/char/agp/generic.c-1214-}\ndrivers/char/agp/generic.c-1215-EXPORT_SYM